    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT75-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">talaimakaṉ varavuṇarttiya pāṇaṟkut talaimakaḷ kūṟiyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Spoken by HER to the bard who had announced HIS coming.</p>
          </div>



        <div xml:id="KT75">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                nīkaṇ ṭaṉaiyō kaṇṭārkkēṭ ṭaṉaiyō</l>
<l>                voṉṟu teḷiya nacaiyiṉa moḻimō</l>
<l>                veṇkōṭ ṭiyāṉai cōṇai paṭiyum</l>
<l>                poṉmali pāṭali peṟīiyar</l>
<l>                yārvāyk kēṭṭaṉai kātalar varavē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Did you see [it] or have you heard from those who have seen?</l>
          <l>One thing we yearn<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">nacaiyiṉam</term>: this form could be analysed as a p.a. 1.pl., but the aspect would be problematic, then. The second possibility is to take it as a pronominal noun (<term xml:lang="ta">nacai</term> + obl. + 1st pl.).</note> to be clear:</l>
          <l rend="indent4">speak</l>
          <l>– may you obtain (the town) Pāṭali, full of gold,</l>
          <l rend="indent">
            <choice>
                <seg>settling on the [river] Cōṇai with [her] white-tusked elephants – </seg>
                <seg>where white-tusked elephants bath in the Cōṇai – </seg>
            </choice>
          </l>
          <l>from whose mouth have you heard that [our/her] lover is coming?</l>

            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
